data.content:
## What happened

This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. In C# 14, `array.Contains(num)` now binds to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees **cannot represent** `Span<T>`/`ReadOnlySpan<T>` operations, so compilation may succeed but the expression tree fails at runtime.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` to force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Either approach forces the compiler to resolve the old `Enumerable.Contains` overload, which expression trees can represent.
